The ID type appears in a JSON response as a String; however, it is not intended to be human-readable. When expected as an input type, any string (such as `"4"`) or integer (such as `4`) input value will be accepted as an ID.

Can either be a `{ hash: Bytes }` value containing a block hash, a `{ number: Int }` containing the block number, or a `{ number_gte: Int }` containing the minimum block number. In the case of `number_gte`, the query will be executed on the latest block only if the subgraph has progressed to or past the minimum block number. Defaults to the latest block when omitted.

enumValues.name: Deceased
enumValues.description: The submitter has existed but does not exist anymore.

enumValues.name: DoesNotExist
enumValues.description: The submitter is not real. For example, this can be used for videos showing computer generated persons.

enumValues.name: Duplicate
enumValues.description: The submitter is already registered. The challenger has to point to the identity already registered or to a duplicate submission.

enumValues.name: IncorrectSubmission
enumValues.description: The submission does not comply with the submission rules.

enumValues.name: None
enumValues.description: No reason specified. This option should be used to challenge removal requests.

fields.name: arbitrator
fields.description: The arbitrator trusted to resolve disputes for the request.

fields.name: arbitratorExtraData
fields.description: The extra data for the trusted arbitrator of the request.

fields.name: challenges
fields.description: The challenges for the request.

fields.name: creationTime
fields.description: The creation time.

fields.name: currentReason
fields.description: Current reason the registration request was challenged with. It's left empty for removal requests.

fields.name: disputed
fields.description: True if a dispute was raised. Note that the request can enter disputed state multiple times, once per reason.

fields.name: evidence
fields.description: The evidence for the request.

fields.name: evidenceLength
fields.description: The request's number of evidence.

fields.name: id
fields.description: The request's ID, keccak256(submissionID, submissionRequestsLength).

fields.name: lastChallengeID
fields.description: The ID of the last challenge, which is equal to the total number of challenges for the request

fields.name: lastStatusChange
fields.description: Time when the submission's status was last updated. It's used to track when the challenge period ends.

fields.name: metaEvidence
fields.description: The meta evidence for the request.

fields.name: nbParallelDisputes
fields.description: Tracks the number of simultaneously raised disputes. Parallel disputes are only allowed for `Reason.Duplicate`.

fields.name: penaltyIndex
fields.description: Stores the index of the last processed vouch in the array of vouches. It's used for partial processing of the vouches in resolved requests.

fields.name: registration
fields.description: True if the request is for registration.

fields.name: requestIndex
fields.description: The request index.

fields.name: requester
fields.description: Address that made the request. It matches the submission's ID in registration requests.

fields.name: requesterLost
fields.description: True if the requester has already had a dispute that wasn't ruled in his favor.

fields.name: resolutionTime
fields.description: The time the request was resolved.

fields.name: resolved
fields.description: True if the request is executed and/or all raised disputes are resolved.

fields.name: submission
fields.description: The submission the request is for.

fields.name: type
fields.description: The request type

fields.name: ultimateChallenger
fields.description: Address of the challenger who won a dispute, and who users, that vouched for the request, must pay fines to.

fields.name: usedReasons
fields.description: Stores all reasons that were used to challenge the request, to make sure that each reason was only used once.

fields.name: vouchReleaseReady
fields.description: True if vouch was not processed and vouchee is resolved.

fields.name: vouches
fields.description: The submissions that vouched for the request.

enumValues.name: Registration
enumValues.description: This is a request to add a profile to the registry

enumValues.name: Removal
enumValues.description: This is a removal request

fields.name: contributionIDs
fields.description: The IDs of the contributions of this round.

fields.name: contributions
fields.description: The contributions for the round.

fields.name: contributionsLength
fields.description: The number of contributions made to this round.

fields.name: creationTime
fields.description: The creation time.

fields.name: feeRewards
fields.description: Sum of reimbursable fees and stake rewards available to the parties that made contributions to the side that ultimately won.

fields.name: hasPaid
fields.description: True for a side when it has fully paid its fee. False otherwise.

fields.name: id
fields.description: The round's ID, keccak256(challengeID, roundIndex).

fields.name: paidFees
fields.description: Tracks the fees paid by each side in the round.

enumValues.name: None
enumValues.description: The submission doesn't have a pending status.

enumValues.name: PendingRegistration
enumValues.description: The submission is in the state where it can be challenged, or accepted to the list, if there are no challenges within the time limit.

enumValues.name: PendingRemoval
enumValues.description: The submission is in the state where it can be challenged, or removed from the list, if there are no challenges within the time limit.

enumValues.name: Vouching
enumValues.description: The submission is in the state where it can be vouched for and crowdfunded.

types.name: String
types.description: The `String` scalar type represents textual data, represented as UTF-8 character sequences. The String type is most often used by GraphQL to represent free-form human-readable text.

fields.name: creationTime
fields.description: The creation time.

fields.name: disputed
fields.description: True if a dispute was raised. Note that the submission can enter disputed state multiple times, once per reason.

fields.name: id
fields.description: The submission's address.

fields.name: latestRequestResolutionTime
fields.description: The resolution time of the most recent request.

fields.name: name
fields.description: The name of the submission.

fields.name: registered
fields.description: Whether the submission is in the registry or not.

fields.name: removed
fields.description: True if this submission has been removed.

fields.name: requests
fields.description: The submission's status change requests.

fields.name: requestsLength
fields.description: The submission's number of requests.

fields.name: seeded
fields.description: True if this submission was part of the seeding event.

fields.name: status
fields.description: The current status of the submission.

fields.name: submissionTime
fields.description: The time when the submission was accepted to the list.

fields.name: usedVouch
fields.description: The vouchee that entered `Status.PendingRegistration` status and is using the submission's vouch.

fields.name: vouchees
fields.description: Submissions the submission has vouched for.

fields.name: vouchesReceived
fields.description: Submissions that have vouched for this submission. Note that vouches given by signature are added when the submission enters `Status.PendingRegistration`.

fields.name: vouchesReceivedLength
fields.description: Number of vouches received.

In the case of `number_gte`, the query will be executed on the latest block only if the subgraph has progressed to or past the minimum block number. Defaults to the latest block when omitted.

fields.name: deployment
fields.description: The deployment ID

fields.name: hasIndexingErrors
fields.description: If `true`, the subgraph encountered indexing errors at some past block

enumValues.name: allow

types.name: __Directive
types.description:
A Directive provides a way to describe alternate runtime execution and type validation behavior in a GraphQL document.

In some cases, you need to provide options to alter GraphQL's execution behavior in ways field arguments will not suffice, such as conditionally including or skipping a field. Directives provide this by describing additional information to the executor.

types.name: __DirectiveLocation
types.description: A Directive can be adjacent to many parts of the GraphQL language, a __DirectiveLocation describes one such possible adjacencies.

enumValues.name: QUERY
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a query operation.

enumValues.name: MUTATION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a mutation operation.

enumValues.name: SUBSCRIPTION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a subscription operation.

enumValues.name: FIELD
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a field.

enumValues.name: FRAGMENT_DEFINITION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a fragment definition.

enumValues.name: FRAGMENT_SPREAD
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a fragment spread.

enumValues.name: INLINE_FRAGMENT
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an inline fragment.

enumValues.name: VARIABLE_DEFINITION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a variable definition.

enumValues.name: SCHEMA
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a schema definition.

enumValues.name: SCALAR
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a scalar definition.

enumValues.name: OBJECT
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an object type definition.

enumValues.name: FIELD_DEFINITION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a field definition.

enumValues.name: ARGUMENT_DEFINITION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an argument definition.

enumValues.name: INTERFACE
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an interface definition.

enumValues.name: UNION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a union definition.

enumValues.name: ENUM
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an enum definition.

enumValues.name: ENUM_VALUE
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an enum value definition.

enumValues.name: INPUT_OBJECT
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an input object type definition.

enumValues.name: INPUT_FIELD_DEFINITION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an input object field definition.

types.name: __EnumValue
types.description: One possible value for a given Enum. Enum values are unique values, not a placeholder for a string or numeric value. However an Enum value is returned in a JSON response as a string.

types.name: __Field
types.description: Object and Interface types are described by a list of Fields, each of which has a name, potentially a list of arguments, and a return type.

types.name: __InputValue
types.description: Arguments provided to Fields or Directives and the input fields of an InputObject are represented as Input Values which describe their type and optionally a default value.

fields.name: defaultValue
fields.description: A GraphQL-formatted string representing the default value for this input value.

types.name: __Schema
types.description: A GraphQL Schema defines the capabilities of a GraphQL server. It exposes all available types and directives on the server, as well as the entry points for query, mutation, and subscription operations.

fields.name: types
fields.description: A list of all types supported by this server.

fields.name: queryType
fields.description: The type that query operations will be rooted at.

fields.name: mutationType
fields.description: If this server supports mutation, the type that mutation operations will be rooted at.

fields.name: subscriptionType
fields.description: If this server support subscription, the type that subscription operations will be rooted at.

fields.name: directives
fields.description: A list of all directives supported by this server.

types.name: __Type
types.description:
The fundamental unit of any GraphQL Schema is the type. There are many kinds of types in GraphQL as represented by the `__TypeKind` enum.

Depending on the kind of a type, certain fields describe information about that type. Scalar types provide no information beyond a name, description and optional `specifiedByURL`, while Enum types provide their values. Object and Interface types provide the fields they describe. Abstract types, Union and Interface, provide the Object types possible at runtime. List and NonNull types compose other types.

types.name: __TypeKind
types.description: An enum describing what kind of type a given `__Type` is.

enumValues.name: SCALAR
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a scalar.

enumValues.name: OBJECT
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an object. `fields` and `interfaces` are valid fields.

enumValues.name: INTERFACE
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an interface. `fields`, `interfaces`, and `possibleTypes` are valid fields.

enumValues.name: UNION
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a union. `possibleTypes` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: ENUM
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an enum. `enumValues` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: INPUT_OBJECT
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an input object. `inputFields` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: LIST
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a list. `ofType` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: NON_NULL
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a non-null. `ofType` is a valid field.

directives.name: deprecated
directives.description: Marks an element of a GraphQL schema as no longer supported.

args.name: reason
args.description: Explains why this element was deprecated, usually also including a suggestion for how to access supported similar data. Formatted using the Markdown syntax, as specified by [CommonMark](https://commonmark.org/).

directives.name: derivedFrom
directives.description: creates a virtual field on the entity that may be queried but cannot be set manually through the mappings API.

directives.name: entity
directives.description: Marks the GraphQL type as indexable entity.  Each type that should be an entity is required to be annotated with this directive.

directives.name: include
directives.description: Directs the executor to include this field or fragment only when the `if` argument is true.

args.name: if
args.description: Included when true.

directives.name: skip
directives.description: Directs the executor to skip this field or fragment when the `if` argument is true.

args.name: if
args.description: Skipped when true.

directives.name: specifiedBy
directives.description: Exposes a URL that specifies the behavior of this scalar.

args.name: url
args.description: The URL that specifies the behavior of this scalar.
